a:1:{i:0;a:2:{s:5:"title";s:45:"Demo Reading Passage - The Great Barrier Reef";s:7:"content";s:982:"The Great Barrier Reef, located off the coast of Queensland, Australia, is the world's largest coral reef system. Stretching over 2,300 kilometers, it comprises approximately 2,900 individual reefs and 900 islands. The reef was selected as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1981 due to its exceptional natural beauty and biological diversity.

Marine biologists estimate that the Great Barrier Reef is home to around 1,500 species of fish, 400 types of coral, and numerous other marine creatures including sea turtles, dolphins, and sharks. The reef generates approximately $6.4 billion annually for the Australian economy through tourism and fishing industries, supporting over 64,000 jobs.

However, the reef faces significant environmental challenges. Rising ocean temperatures have caused coral bleaching events, with the most severe occurring in 2016 and 2017. Scientists warn that without immediate action to reduce carbon emissions, up to 90% of the reef could be lost by 2050.";}}
